/// Budget tick = 400 µs wall. QEMU's LoongArch virt stable counter runs at
/// 100 MHz and TCFG.InitVal occupies bits [n:2] (countdown = InitVal × 4
/// cycles), so 10_000 × 4 = 40_000 cycles = 400 µs. This is the
/// historically-proven scheduling tick — basic test_yield's child rotation
/// depends on it (a 10 ms tick made yield exceed any per-run budget); the
/// wall-clock bound comes from the run tick budget (`BUDGET_TICKS_PER_SECOND`
/// × profile seconds), not from the tick size. Kernel-PPLV ticks at this rate
/// are frequent — safe ONLY because the kernel-PPLV branch acknowledges and
/// re-arms instead of disabling (see handle_user_trap).
const USER_BUDGET_TIMER_TICKS: usize = 10_000;
/// Budget ticks per wall second (100 MHz / 40_000-cycle tick = 2_500/s), used
/// to convert the profile's seconds-denominated run budget into tick counts.
pub const BUDGET_TICKS_PER_SECOND: usize = 2_500;
/// Process rotation happens on every Nth budget tick (250 × 400 µs = 100 ms,
/// matching RISC-V's proven cadence). Every tick still charges the run's wall
/// budget, but the switch path is throttled: each LA process switch copies
/// multi-MB uncached snapshots, and rotating on every 400 µs tick thrashes —
/// 100% of wall time goes to copies and user code never progresses (the
/// pre-P0 tree only survived because the kernel-PPLV disable bug killed the
/// timer early, leaving syscall-driven scheduling).
pub const TICKS_PER_ROTATION: usize = 250;

